commit.message: build: release 0.7.2

Align build and source dir terminology with common usage (#224)

The configure script now refers to the build products directory as
BUILD_DIR and the source directory as SRC_DIR.  Previously it referred
to the build products directory as P_PWD and the source directory as
BUILD_DIR.

commit.message:
Generate headers in the build directory, not the source directory (#223)

The existing behavior was to generate two headers in the source
directory and copy one of them to the build directory.  Now, both
headers are generated in the build directory.  This allows a single
source tree to properly support multiple, independently configured out
of tree builds.

Note that the terminology in this configure script is currently such
that "BUILD_DIR" is actually the source dir (root of the source tree),
and "P_PWD" is the build dir (root of the build products tree).

Co-authored-by: Patrick Kelsey <pkelsey@notforadio.com>

build: Fix indentation

Fix indentation lost well resolving conflicts from github UI.

configure: provide a way to suppress the doc build when doing a make / make all (#222)

* Provide a way to suppress the doc build when doing a make / make all

A variable EXTRA_BUILD is defined, with a default value of 'doc', that
establishes additional dependencies of the 'all' make target.  This
allows disabling the doc build during make / make all by passing
'EXTRA_BUILD=' on the configure command line.

This relies on the fix for name=value command line arg processing.

* Replace inadvertantly removed status line

commit.message:
Correct array parameter notation in CK_PR_LOAD_2() (#218)

* Correct array parameter notation in CK_PR_LOAD_2()

This type of array size notation in C serves only a documentation
purpose.  That the array-size documentation provided in this
macro-templated inline function declaration is not correct for any of
the instantiations would be a minor nit except that gcc versions that
support -Wstringop-overread and/or -Wstringop-overflow use the array
sizes as guidance for when to generate those warnings (errors under
-Werror).

An alternative would be to change the parameter types to explicitly be
pointers - this fix preserves the documentation intent.

* It defies correctness

---------

Co-authored-by: Patrick Kelsey <pkelsey@notforadio.com>

commit.message: Fix the sense of STATIC_LIB in config summary

Fix handling of name=value argument processing

The intent seemed to be there, but the implementation was broken.
This restricts the common value extraction code to operating on
options (i.e., args beginning with '--'), and repairs the '*=*' case
so it properly extracts the name and value.

ck_rhs: Get the right probe to restore on memory failure.

In ck_rhs_put_robin_hood(), on memory failure, restore the right probe
for each descriptor. Descriptor at index 1 will want the probe at index
0, descriptor at index 2 will want the probe at index 1, etc, etc. And
always store the last descriptor slot, so that we know where to put the
last probe.

ck_rhs: Restore the probe number on memory allocation failure.

In ck_rhs_put_robin_hood(), if we try to grow the map, and fail, make
sure we restore the probe number for each entry we changed to what it
was.
This should fix github issue #217.

commit.message:
ck_pr/aarch64: Specify output operands for ck_pr_md_store_*

As in commit 2f9acab, we want to specify output operand widths so that
MSAN compiler instrumentation correctly updates the shadow map.  In
particular, LLVM's implementation depends on having type information for
output operands, even when that's not otherwise necessary.  Without it,
KMSAN in FreeBSD generates false positives on aarch64.

Revert "ck_pr/aarch64: Specify output operands for ck_pr_md_store_*"

This reverts commit affccdc6d0e1af2718dd45a81fa9c3fbf83bf38b.

Mark asked for this to be reverted, and will submit a new patch.

commit.message:
ck_pr/aarch64: Specify output operands for ck_pr_md_store_*

As in commit 2f9acab, we want to specify output operand widths so that
MSAN compiler instrumentation correctly updates the shadow map.  In
particular, LLVM's implementation depends on having type information for
output operands, even when that's not otherwise necessary.  Without it,
KMSAN in FreeBSD generates false positives on aarch64.

ck_queue: add CK_*_FOREACH_FROM

This is a variant of CK_*_FOREACH from FreeBSD queue.h which starts
iteration at the specified item.  If the item pointer is NULL, iteration
starts from the beginning of the list.

commit.message:
Preserve timestamps of installed files

Preserve original timestamps when doing cp of non-built files. That
allows keeping headers unmodified on package upgrades when those headers
were not modified. Gzip keeps timestamps too, so do that also for manual
pages.

Correct mode of shared library to be executable by everyone. Desired
especially when installing by root user.

ck_pr: port to riscv64

The intended consumer is FreeBSD, but obviously this will benefit anyone
wishing to use ck on this architecture.

There are no 16-bit or 8-bit primitives for most operations, as RISC-V
doesn't provide atomic instructions operating on these word sizes.

Sponsored by: The FreeBSD Foundation

build: improvements for riscv platforms

1. Change usage of riscv profile to riscv32. This is a slightly more
   accurate naming convention, as "riscv" could refer equally to the
   32-bit or 64-bit implementation. Keep the alias.
2. Do not hardcode the ABI in ck.build.riscv[32|64]. Since there are
   several valid ABI targets which may be specified, the toolchain's
   default should be used. Otherwise, it can be overridden by augmenting
   CFLAGS and LDFLAGS when invoking configure.

ck_pr_fence_atomic_store(3): correct the description

It should say 'store', not 'load'. The text is identical to
ck_pr_fence_atomic_load(3), so I believe this was simply forgotten when
copy-pasting.
